subSection.paragraph:
Acid deposition is a major environmental concern in much of the industrial world. Acidic air pollutants may affect forest ecosystems through direct impacts on the aboveground parts of trees, as well as through indirect effects on soil chemistry, microbiology and tree roots. Their deposition leads to soil acidification, altered nutrient availability or increased solubility of toxic heavy metals (
Huettl 1993
; 
Ulrich 1983
). Increased soluble Al concentration and the Al/Ca ratio in the soil solution may damage root systems (de 
Vries 1993
). Alterations in mycorrhizal development may be also deleterious to tree growth, because of their important role in plant nutrition. Negative effects of artificial acidification have been observed on mycorrhizae for several tree species (
Blaschke 1988
; 
Dighton & Skeffington 1987
; 
Jansen & Dighton 1990
; 
Vosatka et al. 1991
). Acid precipitation also influences the type, abundance, and activities of microorganisms in soils by altering pH as well as concentrations of N and S oxyanions (
Miller et al. 1991
). 
Newsham et al. (1992)
and 
Wookey et al. (1990)
found the respiration rate and the composition of fungal communities to be affected by atmospheric sulphur dioxide. Soil microorganisms are a substantial part of the diet for many soil animals and changes in their numbers or activity may be accompanied by shifts in the soil fauna.

Acid precipitation on forest floors has been shown to affect the community structure of the soil fauna (
Abrahamsen et al. 1980
; 
Bååth et al. 1980
; 
Hågvar 1984
; 
Hågvar 1987
; 
Persson et al. 1989
; 
van Straalen et al. 1988
). There is much evidence that the composition of the decomposer fauna is partly a function of soil acidity (
Schaefer 1990
). Nematodes are the most abundant invertebrate group in soils. Most of them feed on bacteria and fungi, and their trophic structure may reflect changes in soil microorganisms resulting from pollution (
Ruess et al. 1993
). Studies on their response to manipulation of pH in forset soils indicate that the nematode community is affected by both increased or decreased soil acidity (
Dadhwal et al. 1987
; 
Dmowska 1993
; de Goede & 
Dekker 1993
; 
Háněl 1993
; 
Heungens 1981
; 
Huhta et al. 1986
; 
Hyvönen & Persson 1990
; 
Hyvönen et al. 1994
). Some species appear to be sensitive to air pollutants and could possibly serve as bioindicators (
Steiner 1994
, 
1995
).

Detailed studies dedicated to acid deposition effects on belowground plant parts and associated soil microflora and fauna are scarce. The aim of the present study is to investigate the influence of artificial acidification on nematode community structure in a spruce forest soil. By assessing the amount of fungi and roots, as an important nematode diet, direct effects of acidification and indirect effects via food supply can be determined. As there is need for appropriate indicator species in an ecotoxicological context (
Eijsakers & Lokke 1992
) the use of nematodes for the evaluation on pollution effects in soil ecosystems is studied in this paper.

The experimental site is a 900 m2 plot of Sitka spruce (
Picea sitchensis (Bong.) Carr.
) growing at Glencorse Mains field (55 °51 'N, 3 °13' W) within 2 km of the ITE Research station Bush near Edinburgh (Scotland). The site is located at an altitude of 200 m a.s.l., the mean annual precipitation is 1100 mm and the mean annual air temperature is 7.6 °C. The soil type is a clay loam, on Rawnhill associations-series, Winton, derived from carboniferous shales and sand stone. The soil has a content of % C LOI 10 and the humus form is moder. Previously the land was used in an arable crop rotation (barley). Prior to the planting of conifers, it was covered by mixed, fast-growing grasses.

The amount of fungi in the soil was evaluated using 2 different techniques. One was the measurement ofhyphal length to assess the total mycelial concentration, and the other the estimation of the ergosterol content of the soil, which is related to the active biomass of fungi (
Grant & West 1986
; 
Suberkropp et al. 1993
). Simultaneously to nematode sampling 3 replicate soil cores (12 cm diameter) were taken in October 1993 and April 1994 from each treatment plot and divided into the layers 0 — 2, 2 — 4 and 4 — 6 cm. About half of the soil of each core was taken for measurement of soil pH (H2O) and water content (
Table 1
). The other half of each soil sample was homogenized for 10 s using an MSE Atomix homogenizer at half speed. Afterward homogenization, 3 subsamples of each 1 g (fresh weight) of soil were taken for ergosterol analysis. From the residual soil 10 g (fresh weight) were processed for membrane filtration (only in April 1994) and were homogenized for an additional 10 s in 100 ml distilled water. The suspension was made up to 11, thoroughly mixed, and 10 ml pipetted into 90 ml of water. Of this solution 1 ml was passed under vacuum through a 1.2 pm membrane filter (Millipore, 13 mm diameter) and washed with 15 ml of sterile water containing 3 drops of cotton blue (0.05%) as a stain. Six filters were made from each soil sample. Filters were removed and mounted on microscope slides in immersion oil as a ‘clearing ’ agent. Hyphal length was determined from the number of intersections with a grid system on an eyepiece graticule (
Olson 1950
).

Root growth was assessed by estimating the potential of root systems to extend into a uniform inert growth medium (
Neill 1992
). In both treatment plots root ingrowth cores (12 replicates each) were established by removing soil cores of 10 cm diameter (16 cm deep) and back filling the hole with sand. To minimise disturbance effect of live roots during placement in the soil profiles, the root ingrowth cores were set out in spring (April 1993) when root growth is low (
Deans 1979
). Root ingrowth cores were harvested in November 1993 by removing a central core (9 cm diameter, 13 to 16 cm deep) from the sand. A simultaneously sampling to nematode and fungal samples was not possible by using this method.

The fine roots were evaluated under dissection microscope into 5 classes of root tip development and for 3 vitality degrees. The number of root tips for all classes were counted. The different classes of root tip development are 1 (root initiation), 2 (elongated root tip with root hairs), 3 (tip slightly swollen), 4 (tip considerably swollen or clubbed, first mycorrhizal structures) and 5 (fully developed mycorrhiza) (for details see 
Chmelíková et al. 1992
). The vitality degrees of the root tips are turgid (young tip which is assumed to be absorptively functioning), shrivelled (older tip, live and functioning vascular tissues, but absorptively nonfunctioning) and dead (for details see 
Kocourek & Bystřičan 1989
).

In October 1993 more viable hyphae (ergosterol) were observed in 0 — 2 cm of the acidified plots compared to the control. In April 1994, 5 months after the last acid treatment, and an increase of the soil pH from 4.0 to 4.5 at the acidified plots (see 
Table 1
), more ergosterol was found in the control plots in all soil depths. These effects were significant (P <0.05) in the 2 — 4 and 4 — 6 cm layers. Hyphal length (total) in April 1994 showed similar distribution pattern as for ergosterol in October 1993, but differences between treatments were not significant.

The ‘regeneration potential’ of fine roots was quantified by root ingrowth cores harvested in November 1993 after 7 months. The amount of fine roots grown into the sand cores was higher at the acid mist treated plots (5.2 + 5.3 mm/cm3) compared to the control plots (3.1 ± 2.8 mm/cm3). However, variations within replicate samples were high and differences between treatments not significant. The root tip density, with 3.3 ± 2.4 tips/cm at the control and 3.5 ± 2.8 tips/cm at the acidified plots, was similar. Acid mist precipitation seems to accelerate mycorrhizal development in roots (
Table 2
). The density of fully developed mycorrhizae (phase 5), as well as the occurrence of shrivelled (older) root tips was greater at the acid treated plots. No dead root tips were found in the ingrowth cores.

The population density of the nematode fauna in 0 — 6 cm soil depth ranged between 232 and 392 Ind/g DW or 1.9 and 3.1 x 106 Ind/m2, respectively (
Table 5
). As for many soil animals, the horizontal distribution of the nematodes was aggregated. Great differences were observed between replicate soil cores; for example in October 1993 between 677 and 1883 individuals per core were found at the control plots. Overall, more than 83 % of all nematodes were observed in the upper soil layer. Numbers decreased strongly with soil depth, but differences between treatments were generally low.

The proportion (%) of juveniles and males among the nematode population ranged between 65.4 to 82.4% and 0.8 to 3.3%, respectively (
Table 5
). Their frequency showed no distinct differences with depth. For both treatments high proportions of juveniles were correlated with low numbers of species observed in the samples (a = 0.05 in April 1994). At both sampling dates the occurrence of juveniles was slightly higher, and the occurrence of males slightly lower, in the acidified plots. These differences were significant (P <0:001) only in 0 — 2 cm soil depth in April 1994 for the juvenile nematodes.

Generally the bacterial feeders, which contributed 33 — 54% of the nematode fauna, were the most abundant trophic group (
Fig. 2
). Next in frequency were the fungal and the plant feeding nematodes with contributing of 13 — 36% and 10 — 39%, respectively. Omnivores, predators and unicellular eucaryote feeders made up only minor parts of the nematode fauna. The distribution of the trophic groups changed with the soil depth. Bacterial and fungal feeders were most frequent in the upper soil layer, while plant feeders gained importance with depth. Omnivores and predators occurred mainly in 2 — 6 cm, and unicellular eucaryote feeders in 2 — 4 cm soil depth.

Effects of the acidification differed between groups (
Fig. 2
). Among the bacterial feeders no distinct changes could be observed. Plant feeders were more frequent in 0 — 2 cm soil depth of the control plots. In deeper soil layers their occurrence was quite similar in both treatments. Marked effects on fungal hyphae feeding nematodes were noticed in October 1993, when the acid treatment was still applied. They were more frequent in the acidified plots, especially in 0 — 2 cm depth, but differences were not significant. In April 1994 fungal feeders occurred in similar numbers at both treatment plots. Although these results fit well with the increase of the soil pH and the decrease in active fungal hyphae at the acid mist plots in April 1994, no correlations between fungal feeders, pH or ergosterol content of the soil could be observed.

Pollution stresses such as increased acid or N deposition affect forest soils. Typical acidifiers are the anthropogenic air pollutants SO 2 and NO X; their effects as mixed acidic solutions (H 2 SO4 and NH4NO3) were investigated in the present work. The soils were slightly acid (pH 5.0) and deposition of acid mist led to a decrease of the soil pH, especially in the upper soil layer (pH 4.0). Many soil chemical processes relate to soil solution pH, and acidification is likely to increase the leaching of Ca and Mg from the soil (
Huettl 1993
). In this critical range pH changes also influence the mobility of Al (
Raab & Stumm 1993
) and soil nutrient cycling (
Johnson et al. 1993
; 
Prenzel 1994
). The adsorption of SO4, NO 3 and PO4 by soils is dependent on solution pH, and a decline in pH from 5.0 to 4.0 might reduce the concentration of P in solution by 10-fold (
Binkley 1992
).

All these alterations in soil chemistry are of great importance for tree nutrition and growth, as well as for soil microorganisms and fauna. Acid precipitation can decrease microbial biomass N and change microbial population assemblages even when no pH changes are evident (
Lützow et al. 1992
; 
Miller et al. 1991
). Generally, fungi have lower pH-optima in soil than the majority of bacteria, and a decrease of soil pH leads to a shift towards fungal growth. This fits well with the observed active fungal biomass, measured as the ergosterol content of the soil, which was higher at the acidified plots in the upper soil layer. Ergosterol is the prominent sterol in most fungi, but only a minor component in bacteria or higher plants (
Weete 1980
). It is rapidly degraded after cell death, so that only viable hyphae are detected with this method. Five months after the end of the acid treatment fungal activity was lower, and the amount of total fungal mycelia was higher compared to the control. Similar results were obtained on alkaline dust polluted sites with a strong pH increase (
Bååth et al. 1992
; 
Fritze 1991
). This could be caused by the relatively quick change in the soil solution pH and a successive shift in the microfungal species composition (
Bååth & Arnebrant 1993
). The concentration of ergosterol is species-specific and dependent on the age of the mycelium (
Gessner & Chauvet 1993
), and changes in the community structure therefore can lead to alterations. On the other hand, the discrepancy between the ergosterol content and the total mycelia mass could be due to the fact that the latter includes both living and dead hyphae. This suggests that, after the increase of the pH at the acid mist plots more dead hyphae were present.

The distribution of roots is related to several soil properties. 
Sainju & Good (1993)
found root density positively correlated with organic C, total N or water soluble P, and negatively with soil pH. In the present experiment a mixture of sulphuric acid and ammonium nitrate was applied on the plots. Acidification and its negative effects on roots therefore could be superimposed by a positive influence of the added N (see also 
Brunner & Scheidegger 1995
). The acid mist treatment caused an acceleration of fine root and mycorrhizal development and their senescence (
Table 2
). This could be due to a better N supply, as well as to a higher root turnover, caused by a persistent acidification stress impact on the trees. However, no visible above-ground damage on needles was observed (
Crossley et al. 1992
). In addition to root density, the symbiosis between root tips and mycorrhizal fungi is important for the functioning of the root system. Soil acidification as well as nitrogen amendments can influence the development of ectomycorrhiza negatively (
Arnebrant 1994
; 
Meyer et al. 1988
; 
van Praag et al. 1994
; 
Schneider et al. 1989
). The frequency of shrivelled, absorptively non-functioning mycorrhizal formations increased slightly at the acid mist plots, suggesting a higher root turnover as mentioned above. However, no differences were statistically significant because of a very high variation between single trees. This variability is demonstrated by the ingrowth method (
Nadelhoffer & Raich 1992
; 
Persson 1983
; 
Raich et al. 1994
).

In summary artificial acidification led to distinct changes in nematode community structure and to an increase of the active fungal biomass in the soil, which was followed by a shift towards fungal feeding nematodes. This shows that nematodes are interacting with other organisms or components in their soil environment. Variation in soil chemical properties, like the solution pH, will be reflected by the structure of the nematode community. Considering this, and the influence of nematodes in increasing the turnover of soil bacteria and fungi, and consequently plant nutrient cycling (see 
Yeates et al. 1993 b
) investigations of nematode-plant-microorganisms interactions are a central point in the future.
